        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to use band 7 to image the continuum, 12CO(3-2), HCO+(4-3), and 
HCN(4-3) using a single pointing. The desired synthesized beam is ~0.''4, which 
is a compromise between spatial resolution and sensitivity. Two spectral windows
are in the 1875 MHz Frequency Division Mode (FDM) in dual polarization, a 
third window in strictly continuum, and a fourth window using a bandwidth of
937.5 MHz with 488 kHz channels. The primary observing objectives of these 
windows are to obtain deep continuum images, to detect line emission from 
HCO+ and HCN, and to resolve 12CO emission with about 0.4 km/s resolution. The 
requested sensitivity in the aggregate bandwidth is 25 uJy, which will also give
a line sensitivity of about 2.9 mJy at the finest resolution (for 12CO).

Target sensitivities are determined as follows. First, for estimating the 
continuum, we follow the procedure discussed in [7] for creating skymodels. The 
model is projected onto a grid with a sky orientation set to match the target 
system. The debris is assumed to be comprised of mm-sized grains that are in 
thermal balance with irradiation from the central star. The morphology is 
constrained using the results from Clampin et al. [18], which show two large, 
tightly wrapped spirals/rings at ~200 and 350 AU (Fig. 1) with comparable 
optical depths.  Kinematic constraints from previous CO data [21,22] further 
suggest that there is a third ring of material at 90 AU, which is also included
in the skymodel.  The skymodel approximates the system's morphology using three 
axisymmetric rings, which while idealized, still gives a meaningful estimate for
the required observing sensitivity. Each ring is given a FWHM of ~0.1r, based on
the HST image.

Observations are simulated using the CASA 4.2 tasks simobserve and clean. We 
include thermal noise with a Precipitable Water Vapor=1.0 mm. The total flux of 
the skymodel is scaled to 14 mJy at 350 GHz [31].  Simulated observations are 
run with a target synthesized beam width 0.''4 (antenna file C34-4). The results
are shown in Figure 2.

For the model, we find peak surface brightnesses of ~0.3 mJy/beam. The requested
sensitivity of 25 uJy is expected to yield an S/N~10 for large regions of the 
debris system. These simulation estimates are corroborated by unpublished SMA 
observations [21], which detected continuum at about 5.7 mJy with a sensitivity
of about 0.88 mJy and a beam width of about 1.''5. This 6.5 sigma detection 
suggests a slightly higher expected surface brightness of about 0.4 mJy/beam, 
which indicates that our model shown here may underpredict the amout of solid 
concentration in substructure. We still request a sensitivity of  25 uJy to 
ensure that we can detect faint ring/spiral emission with at least 
modest S/N (e.g., regions of about 0.1 mJy/beam as shown in Fig. 2). The 
continuum sensitivity constraint is the most restrictive. According to the 
ALMA OT, a sensitivity of 25 uJy requires about 1.5 hr of on source integration,
which yields a total time of about 3.16 hr.

12CO has previously been detected in the 2-1 and 3-2 transitions [19,21,22]. The
choice of 488 kHz (~0.4 km/s) resolution will allow us to resolve the kinematics
of the disk, while still providing excellent sensitivity. The most recent SMA 
observations detect 12CO(3-2) at about 1 Jy/beam/channel with 0.3 km/s channel 
widths and about a 1.''5 beam.  Scaling the emission to our proposed
observations, we require a sensitivity of about 9.5 mJy to detect kinematically 
resolved 12CO at an S/N~10. Because we need to reach a sensitivity of 25 uJy for
the continuum, an on source integration of 1.5 hr will achieve a line 
sensitivity of about 2.9 mJy in a 488 kHz channel, yielding an S/N~30.

We do not have a good estimate for the HCN or HCO+ emission.  For this reason, 
we propose to observe these lines with the 1875 MHz FDM spectral windows to 
emphasize sensitivity (and 1.13 MHz channels to reduce the data rate).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
